photo.title: BT131.B67 1762
photo.description: Penn Libraries call number: BT131.B67 1762 All images from this book Penn Libraries catalog record Warmoldus Kuÿpers Zÿn Boeck Ms. ownership inscription of Warmoldus Kuypers (1732-1797), a Dutch Reformed minister, in brown ink on front pastedown of an edition of Johannes Boskoop's Gods alwetenheid van David (Amsterdam: Nicolaas Byl, 1762; STCN 299364267) . Born in the Netherlands, Kuypers studied at Groningen in 1753 and served in Curaçao until 1768. He then emigrated to America, possibly at the behest of Isaac Rysdyck (d. 1790, a fellow-student at Groningen and pastor in Poughkeepsie, NY) and first ministered at Rhinebeck Flats and Upper Red Hook/Red Hook Landing, NY (1769-1771); subsequently he was called to Hackensack and Schraalenburgh, NJ (1771-1797), where he initially shared responsibility with (and was seen as the less evangelical alternative to) John Henry Goetschius (pastor 1748-1774) and thereafter with Theodorick ("Dirck") Romeyn (pastor 1775-1784) and Solomon Froeligh (pastor 1786-1823). Kuypers took the conferentie side of the conferentie/coetus dispute and had Tory sympathies during the Revolution (though he was briefly taken prisoner by British troops during their raid on Hackensack on 23 March 1780 and held until he was able to convince them of his bona fides; see Leiby 245). He was, however, no partisan: "Trouble I hate," he was remembered as saying (Romeyn 76). References: Corwin, Edward Tanjore. This manuscript was possibly first owned by Philippe de Croy, duc d'Arschot, marquis de Renty (after 1533), chevalier de la Toison d'Or, and royal chamberlain. Then, formerly owned by Gharles Gilbert Terray, vicomte de Morel de Vindé, then owned by Jean-Baptiste Huzard. It was sold as part of the Huzard collection in 1843 to Charles Louis Adélaïde Henri Matheron, baron de Curnieu, next sold at auction by Etude Couturier Nicolay at Hôtel Drouot as part of the baron de Curnieu collection, 25 Feb. 1986, lot 144, and then sold at auction at Sotheby's, 5 Dec. 1944, lot 85, to Lawrence J. Schoenberg. Penn Libraries call number: LJS 29 All images from this item Penn in Hand catalog record and facsimile
